{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638422"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17706"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10420"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63606"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10433"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELight entering the eye is detected by photoreceptors in the retina, which synapse with bipolar cells. These bipolar cells then communicate with retinal ganglion cells, whose axons form the optic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the response of ON-centre retinal ganglion cells to light stimulation of their receptive field centre?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No change in firing rate with light or dark","Increased firing rate in response to darkness","Alternating increases and decreases in firing rate","Decreased firing rate in response to light","Increased firing rate in response to light"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct response is that ON-centre retinal ganglion cells show \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased firing rate in response to light\u003C/strong\u003E in their receptive field centre. This occurs because light hyperpolarises photoreceptors, which activates ON-centre bipolar cells through sign-inverting synapses, ultimately exciting the ganglion cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo change in firing rate with light or dark\u003C/strong\u003E - Retinal ganglion cells actively modulate their firing rate in response to changes in illumination.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased firing rate in response to darkness\u003C/strong\u003E - ON-centre cells decrease rather than increase their firing rate when exposed to darkness.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternating increases and decreases in firing rate\u003C/strong\u003E - Ganglion cells maintain consistent response patterns to specific stimuli rather than showing spontaneous alternation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased firing rate in response to light\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern characterises OFF-centre ganglion cells rather than ON-centre cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe centre-surround organisation of retinal ganglion cell receptive fields helps enhance contrast detection and edge perception in visual processing. The surround region shows the opposite response to the centre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bipolar cells in the retina can be ON-centre or OFF-centre, responding to increases or decreases in light intensity respectively.","Retinal ganglion cells receive input from bipolar cells and maintain the ON-centre or OFF-centre organisation.","Centre-surround antagonism enhances contrast detection and edge perception in visual processing."],"references":["Brivanlou et al. Mechanisms of Concerted Firing among Retinal Ganglion Cells, https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627300809927, 1998"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63606"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63606"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T20:45:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T00:02:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10420"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com